et.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is that token consumption is not tracked or enforced. The module must read token counts from API responses and enforce a budget. MOCK-MISS: A unit test of budget-enforcement logic in isolation could miss the failure if the module doesn't actually read token counts from the API response (e.g., if token fields are missing from the response handling). Integration test with mocked API responses (returning various token counts in headers or body) verifies the module correctly reads and enforces the budget.","test_description":"Mock the external API to return responses with different token counts (in response headers or body). Call the module multiple times with documents of varying lengths. Assert that each API call's token consumption is recorded and stays within the configured per-call budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration test (mocked API responses + budget verification) correctly tests token tracking and enforcement.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is that rate limit errors are not handled (no retry logic). The retry behavior is local to the module (or coordinated with a retry library). MOCK-MISS: A mock API that never returns rate limit errors would hide the failure. A mock API that returns a rate limit error on the first call and success on the second call can verify retry logic is present. Integration level (mocking the API with controlled rate limit responses) is sufficient; no real network or async delays are needed in the test (these can be mocked).","test_description":"Mock the external API to return a rate limit error (HTTP 429 or equivalent) on the first call, then succeed on a retry